  "prompt": "Why does a zener diode burn quickly?",
  "response": "A Zener diode can burn or fail quickly due to several reasons:\n\n1. Exceeding maximum power dissipation:\n- Applying voltage beyond its rated power rating\n- Generating excessive heat\n- Causing internal semiconductor junction damage\n\n2. Reverse breakdown voltage limitations:\n- Applying voltage higher than the diode's specified breakdown voltage\n- Creating thermal stress on the semiconductor junction\n\n3. Improper current management:\n- Allowing current beyond the maximum rated current\n- Causing internal structural degradation\n\n4. Thermal stress:\n- Operating at temperatures outside recommended range\n- Rapid temperature fluctuations\n- Causing material fatigue\n\n5. Voltage surge:\n- Sudden voltage spikes\n- Exceeding diode's voltage tolerance\n- Creating instantaneous junction failure\n\n6. Poor heat dissipation:\n- Inadequate cooling mechanisms\n- Preventing effective heat transfer\n- Leading to rapid temperature increase\n\n7. Manufacturing defects:\n- Internal material imperfections\n- Weak semiconductor junctions\n- Reducing overall reliability\n\nTo prevent premature failure, engineers must:\n- Select appropriate Zener diode specifications\n- Implement proper current/voltage limiting\n- Ensure adequate heat management\n- Use protective circuits\n- Monitor operating conditions\n\nUnderstanding these factors helps prevent Zener diode burnout.",
